Steps to Reproduce:

1.  create a new directory with a file called main.tsx with the following contents

```
import * as React from 'react';
import * as ReactDOM from 'react-dom';

interface WelcomeProps {
  name: string,
 }
 
 const Welcome: React.SFC<WelcomeProps> = (props) => {
  return <p>Hello, {props.name}</p>;
 }

 class Test extends React.Component<any, any> {
  constructor(props: any) {
      super(props);
  }

  render() { 
      return <div>
              <Welcome name="Mike"/>
          </div>;
  }
}
```

2.  may need to npm install the react typings to reproduce the problem

```npm init```
```npm install --save react react-dom @types/react @types/react-dom```

3. running ```tsc --jsx react main.tsx``` gives no compilation errors.   (I'm running tsc version 2.4.2)

4. in VS Code, there's a red squiggly under <Welcome>:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2461007/29958657-a2d0a15c-8ea8-11e7-8c4e-5d1ddfb36d6d.png)

It's not clear to me why the JSX element should need to have any "construct or call signatures", but this pattern seems to compile with tsc fine and run fine in the browser.

for reference, I also get the same error highlighting in Sublime Text, so perhaps it's an issue with the underlying Language Services server?  I could not find a separate repo for that server, so it was not clear if I should log the issue under vscode versus the Typescript repo, so please feel free to send me elsewhere if this issue does not seem like it belongs here.

