Steps to Reproduce:

1.  create a new directory with a file called main.tsx with the following contents

```
import * as React from 'react';
import * as ReactDOM from 'react-dom';

interface HelloProps {
  name: string;
}

class Hello extends React.Component<HelloProps, {}> {
  render() {
    return <div>Hello, {this.props.name}</div>;
  }
}
```

2.  may need to npm install the react typings to reproduce the problem

```npm init```
```npm install --save react react-dom @types/react @types/react-dom```

3. inside the render function, start typing "this.props." and observe the contents of the auto-complete box. 

4. Since the props of Hello is a HelloProps, the autocomplete should show the members of HelloProps, namely the member called "name"

Here's a screenshot of what VS Code looks like after I type "this.props.".  I expect the member variable "name" to appear in the auto-complete list.
